 - â€œPeopleâ€ is the set of individuals in the organization, with their individual traits, style, experience and skills. It 
includes particularly all its managers: the general manager (â€œCEOâ€), the top management team and the other managers. If we 
take the whole organization, it will include also the other employees , and even outsourcing agents that are closely 
intertwined with the people of the organization in their daily activities.  
 

 - â€œManagerial Mindsetâ€  refers to the principles, values and frames of reference shared by the general 
manager (â€œCEOâ€) and the management team. The â€œpurposeâ€ of the company, its â€œvisionâ€, and its â€œgoalsâ€ are elements of the 
â€œmanagerial mindsetâ€ and express the intent and dreams of the management team. The â€œmanagerial mindsetâ€ determines 
what is right, good, and beautiful for the organization â€“ and therefore guides the managers in their choices. 
 

 - â€œStructureâ€ is the organizational structure, i.e. the differentiation of roles, location, information, and authority 
(decision rights) and their integration through a number of coordination and control mechanisms. The structure includes the 
pattern of relations between the individuals and units that make up the organization, be it the formal relations (the â€œorg 
chartâ€) and the informal relations (the â€œnetworkâ€). 
 

 - â€œProcessesâ€ include, in general, the decision making processes in the organization, be it resource allocation 
(budgeting, headcount and capex planning,â€¦), conflict resolution, and the handling of exceptions. Specifically, it includes 
information processes and people processes. (N.B. These are the processes that make the organization be (the â€œphysiologyâ€ of 
the organization), not the activities/processes that are elements of â€œStrategyâ€(such as delivering a solution to a client).  
 

 - â€œPerformance Metricsâ€ is the set of indicators (quantitative and qualitative) used in the company to measure 
the individual, unit, and organization level performance.    
 

 - â€œIncentivesâ€ include the instruments of recognition, retribution, and motivation of managers -- and other 
employees -- for their own performance: the salaries and equivalent; the bonus systems and other special  rewards; and the 
career and promotion rules. 
 

